      <h1>How to Choose the Right MIPI Cable for Your Robot Camera</h1>

      <p>Selecting the correct MIPI CSI-2 cable is critical for getting clean, reliable image data from your camera sensor to your processor. A wrong cable choice can cause image corruption, intermittent failures, or complete signal loss — problems that are extremely difficult to debug after your robot is assembled.</p>

      <p>This guide walks through the key parameters you need to consider.</p>

      <h2>1. Lane Count: How Many Lanes Do You Need?</h2>
      <p>MIPI CSI-2 uses differential data lanes to transmit image data. More lanes = more bandwidth.</p>

      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Lane Count</th><th>Max Data Rate</th><th>Typical Use Case</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>1-Lane</td><td>~500 Mbps</td><td>Low-res sensors (VGA, 1MP)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2-Lane</td><td>~1 Gbps</td><td>Medium-res sensors (2MP-5MP, 30fps)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>4-Lane</td><td>~2-4 Gbps</td><td>High-res sensors (8MP+, 4K, high fps)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p><strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> Match the lane count to your sensor's output capability. A 4-Lane sensor on a 1-Lane cable will not work. A 1-Lane sensor on a 4-Lane cable works but wastes money.</p>

      <h2>2. Connector Pitch: Get This Right First</h2>
      <p>The connector pitch (pin spacing) must match both your sensor board and your processor board.</p>

      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Pitch</th><th>Common Connectors</th><th>Typical Application</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>0.4mm</td><td>Hirose DF40</td><td>Compact camera modules</td></tr>
          <tr><td>0.5mm</td><td>Hirose FH12, FH26</td><td>Standard CSI-2 modules</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1.0mm</td><td>JST, Molex</td><td>Prototyping, larger sensors</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p><strong>This is the #1 mistake people make.</strong> Always verify the pitch on both ends before ordering a cable.</p>

      <h2>3. Shielding: Critical for Robotics</h2>
      <p>In a robot, there are motors, PWM signals, and wireless transmitters — all of which generate EMI that can corrupt MIPI signals.</p>

      <h3>Minimum shielding requirements:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Aluminum foil shield</strong> (inner layer): 100% coverage</li>
        <li><strong>Copper braid shield</strong> (outer layer): 85%+ coverage</li>
        <li><strong>Drain wire</strong>: Connected to GND on both ends</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>How to verify:</h3>
      <p>Ask your supplier for the shielding coverage percentage. If they cannot answer or say "standard shielding," that is a red flag. Look for specific numbers.</p>

      <h2>4. Cable Length and Signal Integrity</h2>
      <p>MIPI CSI-2 is designed for short-distance communication. As cable length increases, signal degradation increases.</p>

      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Length</th><th>Risk Level</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>50-150mm</td><td>Safe</td><td>Optimal range</td></tr>
          <tr><td>150-300mm</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Good shielding required</td></tr>
          <tr><td>300-500mm</td><td>Caution</td><td>Premium coaxial cable needed</td></tr>
          <tr><td>500mm+</td><td>Risky</td><td>Consider GMSL or FPD-Link instead</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p><strong>If your cable needs to be longer than 500mm, MIPI may be the wrong choice.</strong> Consider GMSL (Gigabit Multimedia Serial Link) or FPD-Link III, which are designed for long-distance serdes communication.</p>

      <h2>5. Impedance Matching</h2>
      <p>MIPI CSI-2 uses 90-ohm differential impedance. Using a cable with mismatched impedance causes signal reflections and data corruption.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Standard MIPI cable: <strong>90 Ohm +/-10%</strong></li>
        <li>Do NOT substitute with USB cable (90 ohm but different construction)</li>
        <li>Do NOT substitute with HDMI cable (100 ohm)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Quick Checklist</h2>
      <p>Before ordering, confirm:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Sensor model and lane count</li>
        <li>Connector pitch on both ends</li>
        <li>Required cable length</li>
        <li>Shielding specification (foil + braid coverage %)</li>
        <li>Operating temperature range</li>
        <li>Any special environmental requirements (oil resistance, vibration)</li>
      </ul>

      <hr/>
